In order to clean up the hate crime dataset, the column names were changed to reflect names that were both easier to read and more descriptive of the content within them. The whitespace between column names was replaced with an underscore to align with Python conventions and best practices and increase readability and compatibility. The next steps look for both null values and duplicate values in the dataset. Finally, rows with null values were dropped from the dataset. It is important to ensure that the data we are using is obtained legally and provides accurate information about the crimes. The risk that could be created based on the transformations done is the removal of a row containing a null value that may include additional important values elsewhere. No assumptions were made in cleaning/transforming the data. The dataset was sourced from the Federal Bureau of Investigation - Crime Data Explorer, indicating its credibility and reliability. Given it originated from the FBI, we can confidently assert that the acquisition of this data was conducted ethically, adhering to legal and regulatory guidelines.

In order to clean up the FBI’s Crime in the United States by State (2019) dataset, the column names were changed to remove numbers that were superscripted on some of the column titles as well as to name the unnamed column that existed. The whitespace between column names was replaced with an underscore to align with Python conventions and best practices and increase readability and compatibility. The next steps look for both null values and duplicate values in the dataset. Rows with null values were changed from NaN to NA since the cells were technically not empty but were cells that did not require input and were more so meant to be data-less. The final step was to create a hierarchical index that would provide a structured way to organize and represent the dataset, increase readability, and make it cleaner. It is important to ensure that the data we are using is obtained legally and provides accurate information about the crimes. I do not believe that there were any risks that may have been created based on the transformations done as the data was not changed other than the change from NaN to NA. No assumptions were made in cleaning/transforming the data. The dataset was sourced from the Federal Bureau of Investigation website through their Uniform Crime Reporting Program, indicating its credibility and reliability. Given it originated from the FBI, we can confidently assert that the acquisition of this data was conducted ethically, adhering to legal and regulatory guidelines.

category_counts = joined_df['Hate_Crime_Motivation'].value_counts()

# reverse the order of the category counts
category_counts = category_counts[::-1]

# plotting a bar plot
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 6))
plt.barh(category_counts.index, category_counts.values)
plt.xlabel('Count')
# plt.xticks(rotation = 90)
plt.ylabel('Bias')
plt.title('Count of Occurrences in Bias Column')
plt.show()

The aim here is to analyze the occurrences of different categories in the Hate_Crime_Motivation/Bias column of the joined dataset and visualize the results using a horizontal bar plot. Initially, the occurrences of each category are counted using the value_counts() function, providing insight into the frequency distribution of motivations behind hate crimes. The order of the category counts is then reversed to present the categories from the least to the most frequent. The resulting horizontal bar plot displays each category on the y-axis and its corresponding count on the x-axis, offering a clear visualization of the distribution of hate crime motivations. This visualization facilitates understanding of which motivations are most prevalent in the dataset, providing valuable insights into patterns and trends related to bias-motivated crimes. The visualization highlights a pronounced impact of hate crimes on individuals from the Black or African-American demographic.

By annotating the bars with the minimum and maximum values, the visualization highlights the states with the lowest and highest occurrences, respectively. This additional information aids in understanding the range and distribution of occurrences across states, offering valuable insights for further analysis and interpretation.

Relationship between Juvenile and Adult Victims by State

In [54]:
# filter out rows where the state is not 'Federal'
filtered_df = hate_crime_stats[hate_crime_stats['State_Name'] != 'Federal']

# get unique states and assign a color to each state
unique_states = filtered_df['State_Name'].unique()
colors = plt.cm.tab20b.colors[:len(unique_states)]  # choose a color map and get colors for each state

# create a color dictionary mapping states to colors
color_dict = {state: color for state, color in zip(unique_states, colors)}

# plot a scatter plot with different colors for each state
plt.figure(figsize = (10, 8))
for state, color in color_dict.items():
    state_df = filtered_df[filtered_df['State_Name'] == state]
    plt.scatter(state_df['Number_of_Adult_Victims'], state_df['Number_of_Juvenile_Victims'], label = state, color = color)

plt.xlabel('Number of Adult Victims')
plt.ylabel('Number of Juvenile Victims')
plt.title('Relationship between Juvenile and Adult Victims by State')
plt.legend(title = 'State', bbox_to_anchor = (1.05, 1), loc = 'upper left')
plt.grid(True)  # add grid lines for better readability
plt.tight_layout()  # adjust layout to prevent clipping of labels
plt.show()

In this analysis, we filtered out rows where the state is labeled as anything other than 'Federal' from the hate crime statistics dataset. Subsequently, we identified the unique states present in the filtered dataset and assigned a distinct color to each state using the tab20b colormap. By creating a color dictionary that maps each state to its corresponding color, we ensured consistency in color representation across the scatter plot. The resulting scatter plot visualizes the relationship between the number of adult victims and juvenile victims, with each state represented by a distinct color. This visualization facilitates the comparison of victim demographics across different states, allowing for the identification of potential patterns or disparities in victimization trends. Please be aware that the graphical analysis presented here only includes the 20 states depicted in the legend. This limitation arises from constraints associated with the colormap utilized in the visualization.

This part aims to visualize the relationship between the 'Bias' and 'Intimidation' columns of the dataset using a line plot. The resulting plot provides insights into the correlation between bias-motivated incidents and instances of intimidation. The final milestone aimed to join all three of the previously cleaned datasets into one dataset. Regrettably, my initial plan to join the datasets based on the State columns fell through due to limitations in accessing the API data in the desired format. Additionally, during Milestone 4, I erroneously assumed I could join the datasets based on offense types, which turned out to be unfeasible. To complete the assignment to the best of my abilities given the constraints, I decided to join only two tables on the bias associated with the crime. To fulfill the assignment requirements more comprehensively, I also opted to conduct an additional join operation in addition to the one previously mentioned. The second join merges the datasets "hate_crime_stats" and "fbi_table" based on the "State" column. It is important to ensure that the data we are using is obtained legally and provides accurate information about the crimes. I do not believe that there were any risks that may have been created based on the transformations done to the data. No assumptions were made in cleaning/transforming the data. The datasets were sourced from the Federal Bureau of Investigation - Crime Data Explorer , the Federal Bureau of Investigation website through their Uniform Crime Reporting Program, and the Federal Bureau of Investigation - Crime Data Explorer – FBI Crime Data API, indicating their credibility and reliability. Given that they all originated from the FBI, we can confidently assert that the acquisition of this data was conducted ethically, adhering to legal and regulatory guidelines.
